Here is the complete Firestore security rules code:


Viewed a file, ran a command, read a file
Viewed a file, ran a command, read a file
Here's the full firestore.rules content and a breakdown of what each section does:

Users — any signed-in user can read profiles (needed to display writer info). Only the owner can create or edit their own profile, with one exception: rating fields (rating, ratingCount) can be updated by anyone signed in, so the review system can recalculate averages.

Records — any signed-in user can read all records. Only the poster can create, delete, or fully update their own records. Writers can only touch the applicants array (to apply/withdraw) — nothing else.

Chats — access is locked to the two participants stored on each chat document. The subcollection messages enforces the same check, and also verifies that the senderId matches the authenticated user so no one can impersonate another sender.

Reviews — anyone can read reviews, any signed-in user can create one (as long as fromId matches their UID), but no one can edit or delete a review once submitted — they're immutable.

Payments — only the requester and writer on a given payment can read it. Only the requester can create a payment record. Updates are blocked client-side entirely — they must come from a Firebase Cloud Function (e.g. after Stripe webhook confirms payment).

How to deploy:

bash
# From your project root (where firebase.json lives)
firebase deploy --only firestore:rules
Or paste directly into Firebase Console → Firestore Database → Rules tab and click Publish.


